VALUES (
  'The Presale Exit Strategy: Assignment Sales and Profit Margins',
  'presale-assignment-sales-exit-strategy-bc',
  'Can you sell your presale before it''s finished? Uzair breaks down exactly how assignment sales work in BC — developer fees, CRA tax rules, BC''s flipping tax, and how to execute a profitable exit without being locked in.',
  E'You are looking at a 3-year build timeline for a presale condo in Langley. A lot can happen in three years. You might get married, you might move for work, or you might just want to take your profits and run before you even have to get a mortgage.\n\nYou need to know your exit options: Can I sell my presale condo before it''s finished? What is an assignment sale in real estate? How much does a developer charge for an assignment fee, and do presale condos guarantee an increase in value?\n\nI am Uzair Muhammad, and I focus on exit strategies. If you buy a presale without knowing exactly how and when you can sell it, your capital is trapped. This guide breaks down the hard truth about assignment sales, the fees involved, and how to execute a profitable exit.\n\n## The Reality of Assignment Sales in BC\n\nAn assignment sale occurs when you sell your contract — your right to buy the condo — to someone else before the building is finished. You are not selling the physical unit; you are selling the paperwork.\n\nIn a rising market, assignment sales are highly lucrative. If you secured a unit at $600,000 with a $60,000 deposit, and the market value jumps to $700,000 before completion, you can "assign" the contract to a new buyer. You get your original deposit back, plus the $100,000 in equity lift, minus fees. Your return on investment is massive because you never had to qualify for a mortgage or pay closing costs.\n\n> However, the market dictates the viability of this strategy. Are presales actually cheaper than buying resale today? Not always. Developers often price their presales based on what they project the market will be worth in three years, not what it is worth today. If the market stays flat, your assignment margin disappears.\n\n## Why This Matters for Your Capital\n\nIf you are an investor, the assignment flip is often the primary goal. But developers are not stupid; they know you are trying to make a profit on their product. They put strict rules in place to control who can assign, when they can assign, and how much it will cost.\n\nIf you are a first-time buyer whose life circumstances change, an assignment might be your only way out if you can no longer qualify for the mortgage at completion. But if you are forced to assign in a down market, you might have to sell the contract for less than you paid, meaning you lose a portion of your deposit.\n\n> Do presale condos guarantee an increase in value before closing? Absolutely not. Real estate goes in cycles. If you buy at the peak and try to assign in a trough, you will lose money.\n\n## How to Execute a Profitable Exit\n\nHere is the exact framework for navigating an assignment sale:\n\n1. **Check the Developer''s Rules:** Can I sell my presale condo before it''s finished? Only if the developer allows it. Your contract will explicitly state if assignments are permitted. Some developers ban them entirely; others only allow them after a certain percentage of the building is sold.\n\n2. **Calculate the Assignment Fee:** How much does a developer charge for an assignment fee? It typically ranges from 1% to 3% of the original purchase price, or sometimes a flat fee of $1,500 to $5,000. This fee eats directly into your profit margin. Always negotiate this fee *before* you sign the original presale contract.\n\n3. **Understand the Tax Implications:** The CRA looks closely at assignment sales. If your primary intent was to flip the contract for profit, the gains are taxed as business income, not capital gains. Furthermore, BC''s new home flipping tax imposes severe penalties on properties or contracts sold within 24 months.\n\n4. **Market Timing is Everything:** You cannot list an assignment on the MLS without the developer''s permission, which they rarely give because they don''t want you competing with their remaining unsold inventory. You need a realtor with an exclusive network of buyers to execute the sale quietly.\n\n## The Bottom Line\n\nAn assignment sale is a powerful tool for generating high ROI without securing a mortgage, but it requires precise timing and a deep understanding of developer contracts. If you buy a presale assuming you can easily flip it for a $100,000 profit without reading the fine print, you are setting yourself up for failure.\n\n> Stop guessing your exit strategy before you sign. Build the plan first, then commit the capital.\n\n## Work With a Presale Specialist\n\nStop guessing your exit strategy. I am Uzair Muhammad, and I build calculated exit plans for my clients before they ever sign a contract. I negotiate the assignment fees upfront and leverage my private network to execute quiet, profitable flips. Book a free strategy call with me today at presalewithuzair.com, and let''s map out your next move.',
